1. c4 e5 {is the most principled response to the English. White's first move
makes 1...d5 unattractive, but does nothing to prevent the other black centre
pawn advancing two squares, so it is natural for it to seize the opportunity
to do so. However, English advocates can argue that 1...e5 is also a tad
cooperative. As we explain in more detail in the notes to Seirawan-Narciso
Dublan, White's fundamental strategic plan in the English is to attack the
light squares in the centre of the board, and so it can be claimed that 1...e5
weakens those squares a little. Once this move has been played, it will be
considerably harder for Black ever to establish a pawn on d5, and so the
English bishop on g2 is likely to have a strong diagonal, pointing towards the
black queenside. --- Of course, the other point about 1...e5 is that it
produces a Sicilian Defence, with colours reversed and White having a move in
hand. Some people argue that, since the Sicilian is regarded as one of Black's
best defences to 1 e4, and good enough to equalize as Black, then having a
Sicilian as White, with an extra tempo, must give White the advantage. In
reality, this argument is fallacious, for reasons that we explain in more
detail in the notes to Brunello-Brunner. In truth, 1...e5 is a perfectly valid
defence to the English, and should give Black close to equal chances, if
properly handled. Having said that, White players should feel comfortable in
the resulting positions, as they usually represent some of the "purest" forms
of the English that one can get.} 2. -- {The first five games in this section
look at Black playing 1...e5 and 2...Nc6, followed by 3...g6. This kind of
reversed Closed Sicilian produces very typical English structures. In
Seirawan-Narciso Dublan, Smyslov-Liberzon and Petrosian-Hort, we see White
place his pawn on d3, fianchetto his king's bishop, and then employ the
typical English plan of b4-b5, gaining space on the queenside and pressurizing
the light squares. Smyslov-Liberzon and Petrosian-Hort, in particular, are old
classics, and both show how Black's attempts to create counterplay on the
kingside can sometimes rebound on him. --- Miezis-Roemer and Moskalenko-Mestre
Bellido cover the Botvinnik System, which is extremely popular these days. In
this system, White erects the central pawn triangle c4-d3-e4, sacrificing the
d4-square but setting up a position in which he has the flank breaks b4 and f4.
--- Pfleger-Vasiukov, Kasparov-Ivanchuk and Ibragimov-Kuporosov deal with the
classic Four Knights system, in which Black brings his bishop to b4 and
exchanges on c3. These heavyweight structures are some of the richest, and
also most widely-explored English lines, although in recent years they have
lost ground in the popularity stakes, thanks mainly to the increasing use of
the 2 g3 move-order, by which White usually avoids such structures. ---
Taimanov-Hort sees Black adopt the rather rustic plan of putting his bishop on
c5, whilst in Brunello-Brunner we deal with the Reversed Dragon lines, where
Black plays ...d5. --- All of these first ten games see White fianchetto his
king's bishop, but in the last two games of the chapter, we look at
alternative set-ups. Grachev-Lalic deals with Nimzowitsch's 4 e4 line, whilst
Ivanchuk-Karjakin looks at the system with e3. Both are interesting ways to
avoid the most popular and heavily-analysed g3-systems, and in my opinion,
both deserve a closer look.} *

