1. c4 {. QUESTION: What is the point of the English? After all, 1 c4 is not
really a developing move, like 1 e4 or 1 d4. --- ANSWER: That is true. The
English is, first and foremost, an attempt to play for control of the central
light squares. White's initial move stakes a claim for the d5-square, and the
follow-up moves, such as Nc3 and g3-Bg2, will further enhance his influence
over the light squares in the centre. It is true that rapid development is
postponed for a while, but the lack of pawn contact in the centre usually
means that lines stay closed early on, so the slight lag in development is
usually not serious.} ({The plan Black adopts in our main game was developed
as White in the Closed Sicilian, by Boris Spassky. One of the classic examples
was the following game, which is worth seeing, not only for its historical
significance in the development of the white strategy, but also as an example
of how dangerous the kingside counterplay can be:} 1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. g3 Nc6
4. Bg2 g6 5. d3 Bg7 6. f4 Nf6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. O-O Rb8 9. h3 b5 10. a3 a5 11. Be3
b4 12. axb4 axb4 13. Ne2 Bb7 14. b3 Ra8 15. Rc1 Ra2 16. g4 Qa8 17. Qe1 Qa6 18.
Qf2 Na7 19. f5 Nb5 20. fxg6 hxg6 21. Ng5 Na3 22. Qh4 Rc8 23. Rxf6 exf6 24. Qh7+
Kf8 25. Nxf7 $1 Rxc2 26. Bh6 Rxc1+ 27. Nxc1 Kxf7 28. Qxg7+ Ke8 29. g5 f5 30.
Qxg6+ Kd7 31. Qf7+ Kc6 32. exf5+ {
1-0 B.Spassky-E.Geller, Candidates, Sukhumi 1968.}) 1... e5 {By no means the
only move, of course, but the most principled. Black seizes the chance to put
a pawn in the centre, although he does fall in with White's plans a little, by
weakening the central light squares. --- QUESTION: 1...e5 produces a reversed
Sicilian, where White has an extra tempo. Shouldn't this be better for White?
--- ANSWER: Not necessarily. Black defences, when played as White with a move
in hand, often do not prove as effective as one might think. Black does not
have to be as ambitious as the White player would be, in the usual lines,
whilst, paradoxically, the extra tempo can often rebound on White, because he
has to commit himself first. We discuss this issue in greater detail in the
notes to Brunello-Brunner.} 2. Nc3 g6 {QUESTION: This looks a bit unusual.} ({
ANSWER: It is, and is probably not that good - White could now respond with 3
d4!. Black would usually reach the variation in the game by starting with} 2...
Nc6 {.}) 3. g3 Bg7 4. Bg2 Nc6 5. Rb1 {QUESTION: This also looks odd. Why
doesn't White develop his kingside? --- ANSWER: It is all part of White's
strategic plan of pressurizing the light squares. He intends to advance b4-b5,
taking control of the square c6, and driving the enemy knight back. White
judges that he can afford to postpone routine development, in favour of
pursuing his strategic plans on the queenside.} ({Having said that, 5 Rb1 is
by no means obligatory. As we will see later, White has other options, such as
} 5. e3) ({and} 5. e4 {.}) 5... d6 6. b4 Nf6 ({
A more aggressive set-up would be} 6... f5 {. As we will see, Black's play in
this game is a little too passive and he postpones his kingside counterplay
too long.}) 7. b5 Ne7 8. d3 O-O 9. Nf3 {Having achieved his queenside space
gain, White starts to catch up in development on the other flank.} ({
Another way of doing so is} 9. e3 {with the idea of Nge2.}) 9... a6 {QUESTION: 
What is this about? Isn't opening lines on the queenside good for White? ---
ANSWER: A very good question! One is usually advised not to move pawns on the
side of the board where one stands worse, and the text breaks that rule.
However, the move is part of a deep strategic idea, introduced by Boris
Spassky, in the equivalent positions arising from the Closed Sicilian. By
exchanging off his a-pawn, Black gets rid of a potential weakness on the
queenside.} ({
He could instead implement his plan at move 11 straightaway, by means of} 9...
h6 10. Nd2 Rb8 11. O-O b6 {
. However, now we see the difference, as White can play} 12. Qa4 {
, when the pawn on a7 is hard to defend.}) 10. a4 axb5 11. axb5 {It should also
be noted that the game position could - and sometimes is - reached if Black
plays an early ...a5, e.g. 5...a5 6 a3 etc, with a pawn swap on b4 rather than
b5.} h6 12. Nd2 {This is a typical move in such positions. White unmasks his
fianchettoed bishop, which exerts pressure down the long diagonal, against the
central light squares and the black queenside. We already see White's standard
English plan in action - his pawn chain b5-c4-d3 controls the central light
squares, and his c3-knight and g2-bishop supplement the pressure on the
squares d5 and e4.} Rb8 13. O-O b6 14. Ra1 Bb7 $6 {QUESTION: What is wrong
with this move? Isn't it logical to exchange White's fianchettoed bishop? ---
ANSWER: Yes and no. Ordinarily, such an exchange would weaken the white king,
but here, it also weakens the central light squares further. These squares are
the main object of White's attack, so exchanging off a key defender of them
plays into White's hands.} ({It would perhaps be better to play} 14... Be6 15.
Ra7 Rc8 {, keeping the bishop.}) 15. Bxb7 Rxb7 16. e3 Nd7 17. Ba3 f5 18. Bb4
Nf6 19. Qf3 {See the note to Black's 14th. The white queen exerts powerful
pressure down the long diagonal. Notice how consistently White pursues the
plan, announced by his very first move - pressure against the central light
squares.} Rb8 20. Ra7 Rc8 {This position illustrates the defensive plan begun
by Black at move 9. He has offloaded his a-pawn, and put his b-pawn on b6. His
only weakness on the queenside is the c7-pawn, and now he places the rook in
position to defend it. The whole plan looks rather passive, but the point is
that the c7-pawn is not that easy for White to attack further - a point so
deep in enemy territory is always easier for the defender to defend, than for
the opponent to attack. Black hopes that he will now have time to create
counterplay on the kingside. --- As mentioned earlier, the plan Black has
adopted here was developed as White in the Closed Sicilian, by Boris Spassky.
See the notes to White's first move. In the present case, Black's problem is
that he is much less well-prepared for a kingside counterattack than was
Spassky in the above game. As a result, Black's position here is much more
passive.} 21. Qg2 {QUESTION: What is the point of this move? --- ANSWER: There
are several ideas. One is to remove the queen from tactical tricks based on ...e5-e4. Another is to free the white f-pawn, which can sometimes advance to f4,
so as to stop Black's kingside pawn advance (especially the thrust ...f5-f4),
and also to intensify the white pressure against the black centre pawns.} h5 {
This looks a little slow.} ({The move} 21... f4 {is more natural, when it
would clearly be suicidal for White to capture twice on f4. Instead, he could
try} 22. Qh3 {(another point of White's last move), with further pressure on
the light squares.}) 22. Rfa1 Bh6 23. Rb7 Qd7 24. Raa7 {White has succeeded in
bringing further pressure to bear on the c7-pawn, but, as we see, it is still
adequately defended.} h4 $2 ({Black should play} 24... Qd8 {, meeting the
tactical threat of Rxb6. White would retain a definite positional advantage,
but it is not obvious how best to increase the pressure. It is not possible to
attack c7 any further, so White should probably continue} 25. Nb3 {with the idea of switching pressure to the centre after d3-d4. Instead, Narciso decides to
jettison material, in order to set his kingside attack going, but this proves
inadequate.}) 25. Rxb6 hxg3 26. hxg3 f4 $2 {This must have been an oversight.}
27. Rxd6 $1 {Whoops! Another pawn goes, and with it, the foundations of
Black's central edifice.} Qg4 28. Rxf6 $1 {Winning even more material.} Rxf6
29. Bxe7 Rf7 30. gxf4 $1 {Not the only way of winning, but a neat method of
disposing of Black's counterplay. White will emerge with a hatful of pawns for
the exchange.} Qxg2+ 31. Kxg2 Rxe7 32. Nd5 Rf7 33. fxe5 Bg5 34. Ne4 {The dominant positions of the two white knights on d5 and e4 are very thematic for the
English, and crown White's central light-square strategy most appropriately.}
Bd8 35. b6 {. --- An instructive example of the standard English plan of
queenside expansion.} 1-0

