1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. Rb1 d6 6. b4 a6 {QUESTION: What is
the idea here? --- ANSWER: Black holds up the advance b4-b5, and so maintains
his knight on c6. --- QUESTION: But if Black wanted to do that, why not play 5...a5? --- ANSWER: After 5...a5 6 a3, White would achieve his queenside advance
anyway, and the a-file would be opened. The two lines often transpose, but
here, Black has a slightly more subtle idea in mind.} 7. e3 {QUESTION: How
does this differ from Seirawan's Nf3 plan? --- ANSWER: The plan of e3 and Nge2
has several advantages over Nf3: White keeps open the long diagonal of his
bishop, and is also well prepared to advance f2-f4, so as to hold up the black
kingside attack. --- QUESTION: So is e3 and Nge2 just better than Nf3? ---
ANSWER: Not necessarily, although it is probably more popular in this position.
The main downside of 7 e3 is that it weakens the light squares around the
white king, especially f3, which can become a problem later.} f5 {QUESTION: This looks more logical than Narciso's ...Nf6 plan. --- ANSWER: It is, in that it
pursues the kingside counterplay more actively. However, every pawn move
creates a weakness, and, furthermore, here White is well prepared to advance
f2-f4, to stop the black f-pawn in its tracks. There is an argument that, with
White already committed to e3, Black should hold back the f-pawn and play ...Be6-Qd7, so as to be able to exchange the Bg2. With the light squares round
the white king that much weaker after the move 7 e3, this is quite a logical
plan for Black.} 8. Nge2 Nf6 9. d3 O-O 10. O-O Bd7 $6 {QUESTION: Why don't you
like Black's last move? --- ANSWER: Because it does not fit in with the
prophylactic plan on the queenside, begun by 6...a6.} ({Now that White has
completed his development, he is clearly going to continue with a4 and b5.
Black has a subtle idea here, again developed by Spassky, which starts with} 
10... Rb8 {. --- QUESTION: That looks a funny move! --- ANSWER: Maybe, but it
is based on a subtle tactical point. After} 11. a4 {Black intends to continue}
a5 $1 12. b5 $6 (12. bxa5 {is better here}) 12... Nb4 {trying to block up the
queenside and stop White's play on that side of the board. The point of
Black's 10th move becomes clear after the further moves} 13. Ba3 c5 14. bxc6
bxc6 {when the rook on b8 defends the knight on b4!}) 11. a4 $1 Rb8 {
Now Black is too slow, and the text is needed merely to defend the b7-pawn.}
12. b5 axb5 13. axb5 Ne7 14. Ba3 {QUESTION: Seirawan played the same move in
our first game. Does the bishop always go here? --- ANSWER: Not always, but it
is often good. There are threats of c4-c5 or b5-b6, undermining Black's
central pawn structure.} Be6 {An admission that his 10th move was not the best.
If Black were not going to play 10...Rb8, he could at least have put the
bishop on e6 in one move.} 15. Qb3 b6 16. d4 {QUESTION: This is a different
plan from Seirawan's Bb4, Ra1-a7 in the previous game? --- ANSWER: Yes.
Smyslov takes immediate action in the centre, taking advantage of the position
of his knight on e2 (in the previous game, the knight was on d2). Now Black
does not really want to allow dxe5 dxe5, when White would bring a rook to the
open d-file, and the a3-bishop would have a strong diagonal. The next move is
therefore almost forced.} e4 17. d5 $1 {An important follow-up to White's last.
Now his knight will come to d4, eyeing up two tempting entry squares on c6 and
e6. Meanwhile, Black has lost almost all hope of a kingside attack based
around ...f5-f4.} Bf7 18. Nd4 Qd7 19. Bb2 {QUESTION: What is the point of
this? --- ANSWER: The bishop has done its job on the a3-f8 diagonal, and now
that White has pushed his pawn to d5, there is no real hope of a c4-c5 advance.
The bishop now belongs on the long diagonal, whilst the a-file is cleared for
a white rook penetration.} g5 {QUESTION: Is this good? --- ANSWER: Black has
to get some counterplay somehow, but, as we will see, this ends up rebounding,
by weakening his own king's position. This is often the dilemma Black faces in
such positions: if he plays passively, he gives White a free hand; but by
seeking counterplay on the kingside, he runs the risk that the attack will
fizzle out, and then his own kingside weaknesses will return to haunt him. ---
QUESTION: An unfortunate dilemma! --- ANSWER: Indeed, but as Larsen once
observed, "Chess is not an easy game, where you can avoid problems"!} 20. Nce2
{This move covers f4 (preventing the reply 20...f4), as well unmasking the
bishop on the long diagonal. White's ultimate dream would be to bring the
knight to f4 and into e6.} Kh8 21. Ra1 Ng6 22. f4 $1 {QUESTION: I thought
White was attacking on the queenside, so why does he advance on the other
wing? --- ANSWER: Smyslov's play is two-wing strategy of the highest order. On
the one hand, Black was again threatening 22...f4, which White's last move
prevents. Now, if he is to have any chances on the kingside, Black must take
en passant, but then, as we see, his own f5-pawn is a significant weakness -
see the note to Black's 19th move!} exf3 23. Rxf3 Ne7 {
The only way to defend the f5-pawn.} 24. Nc6 Rbe8 25. Ned4 {The pressure
reaches critical levels. The threat is 26 Nxe7, followed by 27 Nxf5, whilst 25.
..Bg6 allows the crushing 26 Ne6. Black therefore has no choice but to fish in
troubled waters, with a desperate piece sacrifice.} Nfxd5 26. cxd5 ({As will be
come clear, Smyslov had seen a brilliant combinative idea, but the ruthless
computer points out that} 26. Rf2 $1 {
is objectively stronger. Black has no good follow-up, and after} Nf6 27. Nxe7
