1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 f5 {This move can presage a cruder set-up, based on ...Nf6 and ...Bc5 (or ...Bb4), similar to the so-called Grand Prix Attack
against the Sicilian. However, on this occasion, it amounts only to a
transposition into the main lines.} 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 g6 6. Rb1 Bg7 7. b4 d6 8.
b5 Nd4 {QUESTION: In Seirawan-Narciso Dublan, we saw the knight retreat to e7.
Is this better? --- ANSWER: It is not necessarily better, but it is a
perfectly valid approach. Black knows his knight cannot stay on d4 forever,
but it will retreat to e6, supporting kingside play.} 9. Nh3 $5 {QUESTION: The
knight looks odd on h3. What is the idea? --- ANSWER: It is a very interesting
choice by Petrosian. Putting the knight on h3 is an idea that sometimes crops
up in the English. White's main idea is to avoid blocking his f-pawn (as would
be the case after Nf3) and to follow up with f4 and Nf2.} ({
The more common alternative is} 9. e3 Ne6 10. Nge2 {when White has the same
set-up as in Smyslov-Liberzon, but the black knight is on e6 rather than e7.})
9... O-O 10. O-O h6 11. f4 Kh7 12. a4 Rb8 13. Nf2 {This is the typical set-up
for White in the Nh3 plan. The advance of the f-pawn not only stops Black from
playing ...f4 himself, but also exerts pressure against Black's pawn centre.
From f2, the knight usefully patrols the g4-square, thus preventing the
potentially embarrassing ...Ng4-e3. As we will soon see, White's play in this
type of set-up is not necessarily confined to the queenside. --- QUESTION: So
if the knight is so good on f2, why is the Nh3 plan not seen more often? ---
ANSWER: Despite its advantages, Nh3 is quite a rare idea in this line. The
three-time British Champion, Harry Golombek, was especially fond of it in
several English lines, but most GMs view it with a degree of scepticism. The
main problem is that by advancing f4, White creates some potentially serious
weaknesses in the centre, notably on the e-file, and must be careful not to
come under pressure in that area. In the right circumstances, however, the
plan with f4 and Nh3-f2 can prove very effective, as it does here.} Bd7 14. Qd2
Nh5 15. e3 Ne6 16. Bb2 g5 {Black sets about initiating play on the kingside,
in typical fashion, but in this instance, he runs into a gorgeous positional
idea from the great Armenian.} 17. fxe5 dxe5 18. g4 $3 {QUESTION: What?? Has
White gone raving mad? --- ANSWER: No, absolutely not! This really striking
move looks potty at first sight, but is actually a superb positional idea. At
a stroke, White seizes control of the light squares in the centre and on the
kingside. We have emphasized already in this book that the main strategical
theme of the English is pressure on the light squares in the centre, but you
will rarely see the plan implemented in such a fashion as this. Obviously, it
takes great positional and tactical ability to see that White will not suffer
for exposing his own king.} fxg4 19. Nxg4 Nef4 {Black launches into a tactical
response, but this comes up short. However, it is hard to know what to
recommend. A major problem is that he finds it hard to connect his rooks,
because the black queen has no good square off the back rank.} (19... Qe7 {
would run into} 20. Nd5 {, of course.}) 20. Be4+ Kh8 21. exf4 Bxg4 22. fxg5 Nf4
{This pawn sacrifice is the best chance.} ({The ending after} 22... Qxg5 23.
Qxg5 hxg5 24. Rxf8+ Bxf8 25. Nd5 Bd6 26. Rf1 {is much better for White}) ({
whilst} 22... hxg5 23. Rxf8+ Bxf8 24. Nd5 Bg7 25. Qg2 {
is even worse from Black's viewpoint.}) 23. gxh6 Bxh6 {Black has no real
compensation for the pawn, and White just has to avoid a few tactical tricks.}
24. Kh1 Qh4 25. Qe1 Qh5 26. Qg3 c6 27. Bf3 $1 ({
This is better than grabbing another pawn by} 27. bxc6 bxc6 28. Bxc6 {
, after which Black gets some counterplay with} Bh3 {.}) 27... Rg8 28. Ne4 Rbf8
(28... Nxd3 {was slightly better, but even then, after} 29. Nf6 Bxf3+ 30. Qxf3
{, White should win.}) 29. Bxe5+ {Winning another pawn;} ({
although the computer's preference} 29. bxc6 bxc6 30. Bxg4 Rxg4 31. Bxe5+ {
was perhaps an even better way of doing so.}) 29... Qxe5 30. Bxg4 c5 {
With two extra pawns, the remaining task is only a technical one. White has to
be careful, as his king is exposed and there are opposite-coloured bishops,
but this should not stop him winning. Petrosian carries out the task, and the
remaining moves are of little real interest to our theme.} 31. Rbe1 Rg6 32. Rf3
b6 33. h3 Rg7 34. Qh4 Kh7 35. Ref1 Rgf7 36. Be6 {A nice little joke, although,
as the game shows, it does not really amount to anything more.} Rg7 ({
Of course,} 36... Qxe6 $4 {allows} 37. Ng5+ {.}) 37. Bg4 Rgf7 38. R3f2 Rg7 39.
Qg3 Kh8 40. Kh2 Kh7 {With the time control reached, the game was presumably
adjourned around this point, and Petrosian was able to analyse the position at
home, and work out a plan to make further progress.} 41. Nd2 {And this is it.
The knight re-routes itself, in search of more promising pastures.} Qd6 42. Nf3
$5 Kh8 $5 {A slightly odd moment.} ({I assume both players rejected} 42... Qxd3
{because of} 43. Ng5+ {when} Rxg5 44. Rxf4 (44. Qxd3+ Nxd3 45. Rxf8 Bxf8 46.
Rxf8 Nb2 {looks relatively unclear}) 44... Qxg3+ 45. Kxg3 Rxf4 46. Rxf4 Rg7 47.
Rf6 {is still promising for White, but he has one pawn less than the game.})
43. Nh4 Rgf7 44. Kh1 {This just gets the king out of potential discovered
checks on the h2-b8 diagonal.} Rf6 45. Rf3 Qd4 46. Ng2 {After a longish spell
of piece regrouping, during which little of substance has happened, White
reveals his cards. The strong enemy knight is to be exchanged off.} Qd6 47.
Nxf4 Bxf4 {The opposite bishops are not such a drawing factor here, with heavy
pieces in play.} 48. Qh4+ Rh6 49. Bh5 Rf5 50. Rxf4 Rhxh5 51. Qg4 Rhg5 52. Qf3
Rxf4 53. Qxf4 Qxf4 54. Rxf4 Rg3 55. Rh4+ {. The rooks come off next move, with
an easily winning king and pawn ending. --- A classic English game by
Petrosian, whose lovely positional idea of 18 g4!! remains long in the memory.}
1-0

