1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e5 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. e4 {QUESTION: Aha, another Botvinnik
Variation? --- ANSWER: Well, more like the Dr McCoy Variation - "It's the
Botvinnik, Jim, but not as we know it"! The move was actually invented by
Nimzowitsch, and is named after him. The big difference here is that White's
knight is committed to f3. In the Botvinnik proper, the knight almost always
goes to e2. --- QUESTION: So is this version better or worse? --- ANSWER: In
general, it has always been assumed to be worse, because White's f-pawn is
obstructed, and the advance f2-f4 is an integral part of White's plans in the
Botvinnik. Largely for that reason, the Nimzowitsch Variation has always been
assumed to be fairly harmless and has never been all that popular at GM level.
However, in recent years, it has attracted a few more grandmaster supporters,
notably the Chinese star, Bu Xiangzhi, and the English GM, Tony Kosten, who
advocated it enthusiastically in 'Dangerous Weapons: Flank Openings'. ---
QUESTION: Why is that? --- ANSWER: Well, 4 e4 does have several plusses. In
the first place, Black is deprived of the chance to break in the centre with ...d5. Secondly, the move fulfils the basic strategic aim of the English, namely
controlling the light squares in the centre. If Black does not stop him, White
will follow with d4, securing control of the centre. If this is prevented,
White plays d3, g3, Bg2 and 0-0, and will then look to move his knight from f3
and push the f-pawn. He can develop quite a strong initiative, if Black is not
careful.} Bc5 {QUESTION: What other moves are possible here? --- ANSWER: The
text is one of the two main lines.} (4... Bb4 {
is the other, pressurizing the e4-pawn and so forcing the reply} 5. d3 d6 6. g3
