1. c4 c5 {. With an early ...c5, Black adopts an initially symmetrical set-up.
However, it is well known that such symmetry cannot be maintained forever, and
at some point Black will be forced to break it. He has various ways to do so.
--- In Grischuk-Bocharov, he maintains the symmetry for as long as possible,
until White's central advance d4 forces an end to it. The result is a kind of
Maroczy Bind structure, where White has a small advantage. Jobava-Pogorelov
sees Black adopt an asymmetrical formation, with the moves ...e6 and ...Nge7.
This line was a favourite of Bobby Fischer, who defeated both Smyslov and
Petrosian with it, and until recently it was regarded as one of Black's best
lines. However, the latest wrinkles seem to give White a promising position,
and the line is currently under a slight theoretical cloud. ---
Andersson-Seirawan is another Botvinnik formation, but this time it is Black
who adopts that set-up, placing pawns on c5 and e5. In our featured game, Ulf
Andersson wins a subtle and instructive effort as White. Finally, in
Kosten-Coenen, we see Black adopt the Rubinstein System, with an early ...d5.
This produces another Maroczy-type structure, but this time it is Black who
establishes the bind, and White who fights against it.} 2. -- {The fact that
we should see the same formations occurring with both colours is a testament
to the flexibility of the English Opening. One of the great difficulties of
the opening is that it can lead to numerous different formations, and the
abundance of transpositions makes it very difficult to pin the opening down to
traditional "theoretical variations". However, these qualities are also what
make the English such a great opening, and mean that it is the ideal weapon
for a player who wishes to engage his opponent in a battle where understanding
of positions matters more than rote learning of variations.} *

