{The Mikenas System is one of the nearest things to a traditional,
variation-based English line. It arises after the moves} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3.
e4 {. QUESTION: What is this, another type of Botvinnik System? --- ANSWER:
Not really. With this line, White abandons the traditional, hypermodern
approach to the centre, characterized by the flank observation of the central
light squares, with such traditional English moves as g3, Bg2, d3, etc. In the
Mikenas, White adopts a much more classical, "in-your-face" approach,
occupying the centre with pawns, and threatening to drive back the enemy
pieces with moves such as e5. It is an altogether more dynamic approach to the
English Opening. --- Black has only two reputable options at move three. In
Kharlov-Ospennikov, he plays 3...c5, but, as we shall see, against this White
has a dangerous positional pawn sacrifice at his disposal. In the resulting
positions, even with queens exchanged, White can frequently establish a
ferocious bind on the dark squares, and Black's play can be extremely
difficult. --- In Aronian-Kramnik, Kramnik prefers 3...d5, which is certainly
the safest and most solid defence. However, even here, there are many sharp
lines and plenty of ways for Black to go wrong. The main line leads to a
position where White has only a small edge, but the fact that so fine a
defender as Kramnik was unable to hold the black position shows that the
latter's difficulties should not be underestimated. --- All in all, the
Mikenas has always struck me as a pretty attractive system for White. Its only
real drawback is that it can only be reached by one, specific move-order, and
relatively few black players allow it, but if given the chance as White, I
would always grab it.} *

