1. c4 {. This chapter deals with three of Black's most popular mainline 1 d4
defences, which he can attempt to apply against the English. The Grnfeld
Defence is one of the most frequently seen defences at the top level, and is
thus correspondingly popular at lower levels too, but it does not work
especially well against the English. This is because, like many hypermodern
defences, the Grnfeld is essentially a counterattacking system, which allows
White to set up a big pawn centre, so that it can be attacked from the flanks.
In the English, however, White can hold back his centre pawns, which has the
effect of denying Black the obvious target that he has in the main lines, and
this tends to prove quite effective in practice. Marin-Ris presents the white
set-up I recommend. I think it is quite significant that two of the greatest
Grnfeld practitioners of all time, Fischer and Kasparov, both preferred to
avoid the Grnfeld response 1...Nf6 and 2...d5 against the English. ---
Kosten-Bujisho then deals with the King's Indian set-up by Black. This is
another hugely popular opening at almost all levels, and one of the reasons
for its popularity is that Black can develop along King's Indian lines,
largely within his own ranks, and thus can adopt the KID set-up against almost
any White opening. This universality makes it a very useful practical weapon.
If White prefers not to transpose into a King's Indian proper, then he has two
main English-style approaches. One is a Nf3, g3 and d3 set-up, similar to
White's play in Seirawan-Narciso Dublan. However, this is relatively toothless
against the King's Indian, and does not promise White any hope of a
theoretical advantage. The other system, which I concentrate on as the main
line, is the Botvinnik System, but, for the reasons explained in the notes, I
do not think this objectively promises White any advantage either. However,
the Botvinnik is an excellent practical weapon, since White is able to force
his own, familiar type of middlegame, and it scores very well for White at
anything below top GM level, so I think it is definitely the best choice,
unless White is prepared to enter a mainline King's Indian. --- Finally,
Kasparov-Short looks at English set-ups against the Dutch. Here too, I suggest
a Botvinnik formation against the Dutch Leningrad, whilst the traditional
Nf3-g3-d3 set-up works well against ...e6 Dutch lines. The Stonewall, in
particular, strikes me as rather pleasant to play against as White, if one is
not committed to putting one's d-pawn on d4.} *

