1. c4 {. In the first instance, the English can be used not as an independent
opening system in its own right, but merely as a transpositional device. A
player whose basic repertoire starts with 1 d4 can utilize the English as a
way of avoiding certain black defences, whilst retaining the option of
transposing back into regular 1 d4 territory against other defences.} -- ({
One simple example is when playing an opponent who relies on the Queen's
Gambit Accepted (QGA) as Black: 1 d4 d5 2 c4 dxc4. If one is keen to avoid
this, perhaps because one's opponent is a particular expert, or because one's
favoured line against it has recently sustained a theoretical "hit" and is
temporarily in need of repair, one can open 1 c4. This precludes the QGA
altogether, and poses the opponent a slight problem. He has to be careful not
to be "move-ordered". For example, if he answers} 1... Nf6 {, then after} 2. d4
{(!), we have dodged his QGA and forced him into a position usually reached
via 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4, which is our normal repertoire, but not his.}) ({Likewise,} 
1... e6 2. d4 {also reaches a position that is probably not part of his
regular repertoire. Many QGA experts answer the English with 1...e5, precisely
because it is one reply that avoids any risk of being move-ordered into a 1 d4
system that is not part of their usual repertoire.}) ({Another group of
players, against whom the English can be used as a transpositional tool, are
Grnfeld players. The Grnfeld Defence, 1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 g6 3 Nc3 d5, is one of
the most theoretically developed of all 1 d4 openings, having been very
popular at top GM level in recent years, in the hands of such players as
Kasparov, Anand, Svidler and others. However, by choosing 1 c4, one can avoid
the Grnfeld altogether. As we saw in Marin-Ris, if Black insists on trying to
reach the Grnfeld, by} 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 {, then the lines after} 3. cxd5
Nxd5 4. g3 {are quite pleasant for White, as Black does not have the usual
white pawn centre as a ready target.}) ({
Likewise, if Black is careless enough to answer 1 c4 with} 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 g6 {
, naively hoping for 3 d4 d5, reaching his beloved Grnfeld, then of course,
we can cross him up with} 3. e4 $1 {, after which Black finds himself forced
into a King's Indian instead. --- Naturally, there is nothing objectively
wrong with the King's Indian per se, but it leads to very different structures
from the Grnfeld. The latter usually gives rise to open positions, where
Black has long-range pieces attacking the white centre (e.g. the g7-bishop, a
rook on d8, etc) along the diagonals and central files. The King's Indian, by
contrast, much more often results in a blocked centre, and many Grnfeld
players do not feel comfortable in such structures (the English IM, David
Goodman, once told me that "Grnfeld players are obsessed - they have to open
the position, even when it's obviously not good!"). --- This idea of using the
English to avoid the Grnfeld, whilst allowing the King's Indian, can also be
incorporated into a more general English repertoire. As the reader will have
seen from my comments in the Chapter 5 introduction, I am not all that
convinced that pure English set-ups objectively offer much against the King's
Indian. The Botvinnik System, explored in Kosten-Bujisho, is less effective
against ...c5 than ...e5, whilst the Nf3/d3 lines are also fairly toothless
against a King's Indian set-up. Consequently, even if the white player is
using 1 c4 as his main weapon, rather than merely as an occasional
transpositional tool, there is some sense in answering 1 c4 Nf6 2 Nc3 g6 with
3 e4, forsaking independent English paths and heading back into the King's
Indian proper.}) ({Going back to the idea of using 1 c4 merely as a way of
avoiding certain 1 d4 main lines, it should be noted that the Benoni (1 d4 Nf6
2 c4 c5), including the Benko Gambit (1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 c5 3 d5 b5), can be dodged
by playing 1 c4, e.g.} 1... Nf6 2. Nc3 {, and now:} -- (2... c5 {can be met by}
3. g3 ({or} 3. Nf3 {first, forcing an English line, as seen in Chapter 2.})) ({
. Similarly, the Nimzo-Indian (1 d4 Nf6 2 c4 e6 3 Nc3 Bb4) can be avoided by} 
2... e6 3. e4 {, the Mikenas Attack, as covered in Chapter 3.})) (1... -- {
In summary, the 1 d4 player can use the English as a transpositional tool, to
avoid a number of the main defences to 1 c4. This can be a useful way of
dodging a particular opponent's favourite defence, in a one-off game, and can
also be used as a more permanent opening repertoire trick, for example, by
always opening 1 c4, but then being prepared to transpose back into various 1
d4 main lines, whilst avoiding certain others.}) *

