{The second move dilemma: -- Assuming that White intends to use} 1. c4 {
as a permanent repertoire choice, his biggest decision comes as early as move
2. Basically, the question is whether he should answer 1...e5/1...Nf6 with 2
Nc3 or 2 g3.} -- {"Ich bin ein Kostenite" -- Ever since the publication of
Tony Kosten's groundbreaking repertoire book The Dynamic English, in 1999, the
dominant move-order amongst English Opening practitioners has been 1 c4,
followed by} 2. g3 {. Kosten's book, although containing fewer than 150 pages,
provided White players with a complete repertoire, based on these first two
moves, and proved immensely influential. This same initial move-order has been
recommended by Mihail Marin, in his more recent and much more detailed series
of repertoire books for the white player. --- The advantage of the 2 g3
move-order, as explained by Kosten himself, is to avoid certain of the most
theoretical English lines. In particular, the Four Knights English lines,
beginning 1 c4 e5 2 Nc3 Nf6 3 Nf3 Nc6 4 g3, and now both 4...Bb4 and 4...d5
have a large body of theory behind them, as we have seen in Chapter 1. In
addition, Black has various sidelines, such as 2...Bb4, which Kosten's
move-order avoids. The main point of the Kosten move-order can be summed up as
follows: if White is going to play g3 at some point anyway, then he may as
well play it on move 2. By doing so, he avoids certain heavily theoretical
lines, as well as a few less significant sidelines. --- However, one rarely
gets anything for nothing in this life, and the chessboard is no exception.
The Kosten move-order also has several drawbacks, and now is the time to
consider these.} *

