with ...Nc6.}) ({Instead, Miezis' solution is the move} 5. e4 {. With this,
White clamps down on the d5-square, and prepares to prevent the doubling of
his c-pawns by Nge2. Black usually takes the chance to double the pawns, by}
Bxc3 6. dxc3 {and now} d6 {. --- This is a position in which Miezis has
enormous experience; in fact, Megabase 2012 has 49 of his games which reached
this position. His overall score is a healthy 60% as White, but despite this,
I am not entirely convinced White has any advantage. His plan is to put the
queen on e2 and try to bring the knight ultimately to e3. This can be achieved
via f3-d2-f1, or, Miezis' more recent plan, playing the pawn to f3, followed
by Nh3-f2 and eventually via d1-e3. However, both of these plans are rather
slow, and practice suggests that Black is doing well with a rapid ...a6 and ...b5, seeking to open the f1-a6 diagonal, and embarrass the white queen. The
recent game N.Miezis-M.Adams, European Team Championship 2011, continued} 7.
Qe2 Nbd7 8. Nh3 a6 9. f3 b5 10. Be3 bxc4 11. Qxc4 a5 12. Qd3 Ba6 13. Qc2 Qb8 {
, with a good position for Black, who eventually won a long game. Looking more
closely at Miezis' statistics in this line, it is striking that he has scored
extremely well against lower-rated players, but has lost almost every time he
has faced an opponent rated higher than himself. This suggests it is a line
where the better player will win - that may make it attractive or otherwise,
to potential white players, depending on their opposition.}) *

