{Another Miezis' speciality is his way of meeting} 1. c4 e6 {. Rather than
transposing into a QGD, or adopting a system based on g3, he plays the line} 2.
e4 d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 {. This in fact transposes into a position which
could arise from the Exchange Variation of the French Defence, after 1 e4 e6 2
d4 d5 3 exd5 exd5 4 c4. This in itself should be enough to confirm that White
has no objective grounds for hoping for an advantage, but once again, Miezis
is relying less on objective factors, and more on his own greater experience
with the position. After the almost inevitable exchange on c4, we will reach
an IQP structure, but one where Black has a pawn on the c-file, rather than
the e-file. This changes the position somewhat. In particular, the square f7
can be more vulnerable than usual, with a white bishop on c4 and a knight
potentially coming to e5 (Qb3 is another way of strengthening the pressure
against f7). Similar structures can also arise from the QGA variation 1 d4 d5
2 c4 dxc4 3 e3 e5 4 Bxc4 exd4 5 exd4, where practice shows that Black is
objectively okay with accurate play, but needs to be careful. --- Once again,
Miezis has played this line numerous times - no fewer than 174 games on
Megabase 2012, and with a highly impressive score of 69% as White. Once again,
though, he has usually come unstuck against top-class opposition, which again
suggests this is a line which works effectively again weaker opponents, but
less so when the white player is outclassed by his opponent. Here is a nice
example of how effective it can be, even against GM-strength opposition (see
Miezis-Akesson).} *

