1. c4 {. Objectively, there is not really anything much to choose between the
Kosten move-order with 2 g3, and the classical 2 Nc3, and the decision is
largely a matter of taste. Despite the title of Kosten's book, I actually
think the 2 Nc3 move-order is rather more dynamic than 2 g3, chiefly because
of the availability of more aggressive options, with an early e4, and (often)
dispensing with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop. I personally also
find the option of transposing into some main line 1 d4 openings, such as the
King's Indian, quite an attractive feature of this line, whilst the option of
non-g3 lines in the 1...e5 Four Knights position is an added incentive to
prefer 2 Nc3. --- On the other hand, the Kosten 2 g3 move-order provides a
more self-contained repertoire, with fewer options for Black to disrupt
White's standard English development. Structures such as the Botvinnik System,
whatever their objective merits, can be highly effective in practice, in the
hands of an experienced English player, who is familiar with the ins and outs
of such heavyweight positions. --- At the end of the day, you pays your money
and you takes your choice. As I hope I have demonstrated in this book, the
English Opening is an extremely flexible weapon, which suits many different
players and styles, and I hope that I have helped you improve your
understanding of it. I wish you every success with the English Opening, in
your chess career.} *

